07111nam a22007815i 9780822392156DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223921567 a10.1515/97808223921562doi  a(DE-B1597)554420  a(OCoLC)1224278348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.A1bR32452 2009 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a305.80097322200aRacially Writing the Republic :bRacists, Race Rebels, and Transformations of American Identity /cBruce Baum, Duchess Harris. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (341 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGeorge Washington: Porcelain, Tea, and Revolution -- tJefferson's Legacies: Racial Intimacies and American Identity -- tTocqueville and Beaumont, Brothers and Others -- t"The Sacred Right of Self-Preservation": Juan Nepomuceno Cortina and the Struggle for Justice in Texas -- t"Shoot Mr. Lincoln"? -- tSarah Winnemucca and the Rewriting of Nation -- tThe Politics of the Possible: Ida B. Wells-Barnett's Crusade for Justice -- tMeat vs. Rice (and Pasta): Samuel Gompers and the Republic of White Labor -- tTheodore Roosevelt and the Divided Character of American Nationalism -- tMargaret Sanger and the Racial Origins of the Birth Control Movement -- tW. E. B. Du Bois and the Race Concept -- tDisplacing Filipinos, Dislocating America: Carlos Bulosan's America Is in the Heart -- tLooking through Sidney Brustein's Window: Lorraine Hansberry's New Frontier, 1959-1965 -- tJames Baldwin's "Discovery of What It Means to Be an American -- tAfterword: Racially Writing the Republic and Racially Righting the Republic -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRacially Writing the Republic investigates the central role of race in the construction and transformation of American national identity from the Revolutionary War era to the height of the civil rights movement. Drawing on political theory, American studies, critical race theory, and gender studies, the contributors to this collection highlight the assumptions of white (and often male) supremacy underlying the thought and actions of major U.S. political and social leaders. At the same time, they examine how nonwhite writers and activists have struggled against racism and for the full realization of America's political ideals. The essays are arranged chronologically by subject, and, with one exception, each essay is focused on a single figure, from George Washington to James Baldwin.The contributors analyze Thomas Jefferson's legacy in light of his sexual relationship with his slave, Sally Hemings; the way that Samuel Gompers, the first president of the American Federation of Labor, rallied his organization against Chinese immigrant workers; and the eugenicist origins of the early-twentieth-century birth-control movement led by Margaret Sanger. They draw attention to the writing of Sarah Winnemucca, a Northern Piute and one of the first published Native American authors; the anti-lynching activist Ida B. Wells-Barnett; the Filipino American writer Carlos Bulosan; and the playwright Lorraine Hansberry, who linked civil rights struggles in the United States to anticolonial efforts abroad. Other figures considered include Alexis de Tocqueville and his traveling companion Gustave de Beaumont, Juan Nepomuceno Cortina (who fought against Anglo American expansion in what is now Texas), Abraham Lincoln, Theodore Roosevelt, and W. E. B. Du Bois. In the afterword, George Lipsitz reflects on U.S. racial politics since 1965.Contributors. Bruce Baum, Cari M. Carpenter, Gary Gerstle, Duchess Harris, Catherine A. Holland, Allan Punzalan Isaac, Laura Janara, Ben Keppel, George Lipsitz, Gwendolyn Mink, Joel Olson, Dorothy Roberts, Patricia A. Schechter, John Kuo Wei Tchen, Jerry Thompson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aEthnicityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aIsaac, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaum, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeppel, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaum, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Duchess, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerstle, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipsitz, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Duchess, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanara, Laura1 aOlson, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTchen, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTchen, John Kuo Wei1 acarpenter, cari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 amink, gwendolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 athompson, jerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ajanara, laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aschechter, patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z9783110711837